  "prompt": "What three books should an economics undergraduate read?",
  "response": "Here are three essential books that an economics undergraduate should consider reading:\n\n1. **\"Principles of Economics\" by Gregory Mankiw**: This textbook is widely used in introductory economics courses. It provides a comprehensive overview of microeconomics and macroeconomics, presenting key concepts in a clear and accessible manner. Mankiw's engaging writing style and real-world examples help students understand the practical applications of economic theory.\n\n2. **\"The Wealth of Nations\" by Adam Smith**: Considered one of the foundational texts of modern economics, this book explores the nature of economic systems, the division of labor, and the importance of free markets. Reading Smith can provide valuable historical context and insights into the development of economic thought.\n\n3. **\"Freakonomics\" by Steven D. Levitt and Stephen J. Dubner**: This book takes a unique approach to economics by applying economic theory to a wide range of social issues. It encourages critical thinking and demonstrates how incentives shape human behavior, making economics relatable and interesting.\n\nThese books provide a solid foundation in both theoretical and applied economics, and they should help foster a deeper understanding of the subject for any undergraduate student.",
